<p>&nbsp;For routes between Antigua and Xela, there are daily departures in both directions. The journey typically takes around four hours, with departures from Antigua in the afternoon and from Xela in the morning. Similarly, travel between Xela and Lake Atitlán, particularly Panajachel, is available with a shorter duration of about two hours, also with morning and afternoon departure options depending on direction.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Connections between Xela and Chichicastenango are straightforward, taking approximately two hours. Shuttles depart in the morning from Xela and return in the afternoon from Chichicastenango, with a designated pickup point in front of Hotel Santo Tomás. For longer journeys, such as between Xela and Cobán or Lanquín, the travel time extends to around ten hours, with early morning departures to accommodate the distance.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Travelers heading to or from Guatemala City and its airport can find both shared and private transportation options. Shared shuttles operate from Xela to the city with a journey time of about four hours, while private transfers from the airport to Xela are available at any time, offering flexibility and direct service.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Routes also connect Xela with other destinations around Lake Atitlán, including San Pedro, San Juan, and San Marcos, with travel times averaging two hours. Departure times vary slightly depending on the specific town, ensuring convenient access around the lake region. There are also long-distance services such as from Lanquín to Xela and from Xela to Río Dulce, both taking approximately ten hours.</p>
<p>&nbsp;International routes are available for those traveling between Guatemala and Mexico. Shuttles connect Xela with San Cristóbal and Tapachula, with travel durations ranging from four to ten hours depending on the destination. Return trips from Mexico to Xela are also scheduled, typically departing in the early morning.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Some routes include connections through Antigua, such as travel between Xela and El Paredón. In these cases, passengers may have a layover in Antigua, allowing time to store luggage and explore or eat before continuing the journey. The total duration for such trips is usually around six hours.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Additional services include transportation to Río Dulce, Flores, and the Fuentes Georginas hot springs. The hot springs shuttle includes both transport and entrance fees, with multiple departure times throughout the day and a short travel duration of about one hour.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Antigua serves as another central hub, offering routes to Lake Atitlán, Chichicastenango, and Guatemala City. Travel times vary between two to four hours depending on the destination, with multiple departures available daily. Lake Atitlán routes cover both Panajachel and San Pedro La Laguna, with flexible scheduling to accommodate travelers.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Private transportation options are also available for select routes, particularly from Guatemala City Airport to Lake Atitlán, offering direct and convenient travel without fixed departure times. Overall, the shuttle network is designed to provide reliable, comfortable, and efficient travel across Guatemala’s most popular destinations.</p>
